<theorem xml:id="th_orbit_decomp">
<title>Orbit decomposition theorem</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>G\times A\rightarrow A</m> be a group action. 
<ol>
    <li>
        <p>
            The relation <m>a\sim a'</m> if and only if <m>a'\in O_a</m> is an equivalence relation whose equivalence classes are the distinct orbits <m>O_a</m> of the group action. As a result, we have a partition 
            <me>
                A=\bigcup_{a\in A}O_a
            </me>
            of <m>A</m> into disjoint orbits, and <m>O_a=O_{a'}</m> if and only if <m>a'\in O_a</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            As a <m>G</m>-set,  <m>A</m> decomposes into a disjoint union of orbits, each of which is isomorphic as a <m>G</m>-set to <m>G/H</m> for some subgroup <m>H\leq G</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
</p>
</statement>
<proof>
<p>
</p>
</proof>
</theorem>
<p>
    We end this section with a fantastic result commonly known as <em>Burnside's lemma</em> even though it was first proved (using modern group-theoretic language) by Frobenius. Consequently, some mathematical wags refer to the result as the <em>lemma that is not Burnside's</em>. We confuse things even further by giving it the designation of a theorem! The result allows us to count the distinct orbits of a group action in terms of so-called fix sets, which we now define. 
</p>
<definition xml:id="d_fix_sets">
<title>Fix sets</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>G\times A\rightarrow A</m> be a group action. Given an element <m>g\in G</m>, the <term>fix set</term> of <m>g</m> under this action, denoted <m>\Fix(g)</m>, is defined as 
<men xml:id="eq_fix_set">
    \Fix(g)=\{a\in A\mid g\cdot a=a\}
</men>.
More generally, given a subset <m>X\subseteq G</m>, we define its fix set <m>\Fix(X)</m> as 
<men xml:id="eq_fix_set_subset">
    \Fix(X)=\{a\in A\mid g\cdot a=a \text{ for all } g\in X\}=\bigcap_{g\in X}\Fix(g)
</men>.
</p>
</statement>
</definition>

<theorem xml:id="th_burnside">
<title>Burnside's lemma</title>
<creator>Frobenius</creator>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>G</m> be a finite group acting on a finite nonempty set <m>A</m>, and let <m>O</m> be the set of orbits of the group action. We have 
<men xml:id="eq_Burnside">
    \abs{O}=\frac{1}{\abs{G}}\sum_{g\in G}\Fix(g)
</men>.

</p>
</statement>
<proof>
<p>
</p>
</proof>
</theorem>

